reviewText: This is a B-grade movie, which requires highly developed skills in  suspension of disbelief to be appreciated, but as entertainment it's not a total loss. The motivations behind some of the character's actions are pretty unconvincing but necessary to keep the plot moving forward. Similarly, some of the science is lame (for example, why does the building still have some electrical power? Would the dimension machine really work with unfiltered creek water? c'mon!). Nonetheless, there are a few really, really gold moments in the movie ("don't poke the alien") and cute ideas too (the whole parking-meter thread tickled my fancy, despite the fact that it is another gap in believable science). The acting was good enough and I loved hearing more than just American accents. The special effects were good enough too. If you're a particular fan of any of the actors or themes in this movie, yeah: go for it. If you're after a high point in entertainment... move on; keep searching.
summary: Pretty ordinary, but a few really choice lines

reviewText: I had watched this movie on the SyFy channel, so I knew what I was getting. Flat out, I bought it because it stars Joe Flanigan (Stargate Atlantis).This movie is ok, but leaves so much unanswered.  It feels like a tv pilot that didn't get picked up, so they aired it as a 2-hour movie.  The acting is good, and the story revolves around time/dimension travel (sort of like a Sliders episode...with dino-creatures). Warning - It does get a little gory.Semi-Spoiler: this movie would be much better if it wasn't so open ended.  I would have rated it 4 stars if the story had been fully developed (i.e., actual ending) as a straight out 2 hour movie.If you are a Joe Flanigan fan AND Amazon offers this at a bargain price  - I say buy it!

reviewText: I'm not exactly sure why, but I'm keeping this one for my collection (maybe the lead movie for some future double feature sci-fi monster night viewing?).It's an embarrassingly stupid movie populated with a whole slew of obnoxious bodies (I meant characters).  You have to be suspicious when they start the picture with a room filled with way too many people and then misplace most of them during the first few minutes.  Sad to say, I didn't notice the loss and couldn't have told you who was suddenly missing from the ranks even if tortured.The idea may of looked great on paper but I'm thinking, not.  The plot can be summed up in a few words...with plenty left over.  A mysterious device with peek-a-boo applications transports them somewhere else and they just want to go home.  The film shows you this in only 88 minutes.The special effects aren't that special; when we first see the monster standing outside, it has no shadow.  Not that this was a planet teeming with critters of any sort.  But you'd think they'd at least cough up another buck thirty to throw in a space bird or two.  Nope, just those monsters (I think there were two but then it might just have been really fast and got around by beaming from place to place).  Even when they are being chased by this monster(s), all you saw were the actors running, no sign of what they were running from until they stopped and then the filmmakers plopped in a monster.  Roar!The characters were apparently all standup comics because everyone had jokes for lines.  These especially came in handy just before they were killed.  It always pays to be funny before being cut in half.I especially loved the idea that part of a building was transported to another world (with no running water).....but they still had plenty of electricity!  And of course, it was water they needed for THE device.  Darn, and none on hand.Once again, a never ending supply of bullets for their handguns.No matter how many times they yelled that they were running out of time, they still had plenty of time.  Time they needed to pare down the survivors.  They were mighty stingy with their monsters but of victims they had plenty.I kept thinking poor Joe.  Then I thought, poor John Rhys-Davies!Not much of a Twilight Zone twist ending.Recommendations?  Yeah, I'm still thinking about that.

reviewText: FEROCIOUS PLANETA that silly SyFy Channel and that crazy Maneater Series, yes I love them both. In fact I try to collect as many of these films as I can. I may have reviewed a few of these flicks and so it seems I am reviewing another. This one right here is very much like many other flicks but like them it also has a silly charm to it. Also it stars Joe Flanigan of Stargate Atlantis fame, so that adds to the fun in my opinion. Besides who does not like a creature feature, there is a fun element to them.The government is looking at a device that some scientists have come up with and are interested in it. Well not everyone is behind it of course since it is a device that can transport you to another dimension. While looking at the thing something goes wrong and everyone is transported to another place. This place is full of all kinds of creatures, very dinosaur like. So the group must find a way to not only survive but get back home as well.This is your typical SyFy flick but it is not completely bad, at least the action is good. From the moment they arrive things kick off. As soon as dude goes.........well just see for yourself. The creatures do look cool although the budget strains them, but you can get what they were going for. The action is quick like you would like and helps the film flow. Flanigan does a good job here and it was cool to see him back in action on a SyFy production.This is a decent low budget flick that is not horrible if you like these types of flicks. The film moved quick enough and the picking off one by one deaths kept me interested.  Now this is not for everyone but if you don't mind these bad but good B movies then this is for you. Also there are some completely ridicules things in this flick, you'll see.

reviewText: In approaching a SyFy channel original creature feature, there are only so many resultant options available in terms of entertainment value: (1) The movie can be unrelentingly and painfully bad, (2) it can be so delightfully horrendous that it's camp nirvana, or (3) it can be genuinely frightening or effective. Faithful fans of the network's slate of films will realize that most fall within the first category while only a miniscule few hit that third category. No, as a true SyFy fan, I generally hope for that second classification--cheesy goodness that makes bad movie magic! "Ferocious Planet" is a film that actually blurs the line a bit and the results are surprisingly solid. Strong creature conception and execution distinguish this rather silly tale which retains many amusingly bad moments without ever veering all the way into camp. And this semi-serious tone amidst the lunacy actually works. Mind you, I'm still rating this 4-stars adjusted on the bad movie scale--but if you seek out this type of goofy low budget entertainment, this Planet might be worth a look.The film jumps off right away as a group of Washington bigwigs (led with robust gusto by John Rhys-Davies) visiting a scientific lab to witness the most important experiment of all time! After two seconds of explanatory junk science mumbo jumbo, a fusion generator malfunctions sending the cast into an alternate dimension. Don't you hate it when that happens? The new world looks surprisingly like a small stretch of forest (no big budget sets here), but the group finds out they are not alone. A dinosaur type inhabitant provides some challenges to our unlikely travelers and luckily there are plenty of extraneous cast members for it to systematically destroy. What the film saved in location expenses, it makes up with pretty good creature effects (both a baby and it's adult counterparts) and killing mayhem. The fusion reactor needs repair in order to return home and, of course, some of the humans prove to be their own worst enemies.Many people will undoubtedly be tuning in to this epic to check our Stargate alum Joe Flanigan return to his SyFy roots. As a disgraced colonel, he displays likable moxie. Despite limited character development, most of the actors are fully engaged in their rather thinly drawn stereotypes. In truth, as the film began, I thought we were headed for disaster. The script and plotting are so thin and familiar. But the longer the movie progressed and the more I gave in to the silliness--the more it grew on me. There is a twist ending that I saw coming from a mile away (about 30 minutes into the picture), but I still enjoyed its reveal. There is nothing especially unique in the film's story--we've seen it all before--but there is just enough tenseness, just enough splatter, and just enough humor to keep things interesting. I doubt that I'd sit through this film several more times--but if you like this sort of thing, you can certainly do worse! KGHarris, 4/11.
summary: Surprisingly Solid SyFy Silliness: On The Scale Of Bad Movie Magic, This Rates A Peek

reviewText: Parallel worlds/dimensions is an intriguing premise utilized many times in movies and television.  ScyFy's most recent entry in this scenario is FEROCIOUS PLANET.  It's actually a little better than I expected.  75% of the special fx are decent, while the rest aren't quite as good.  As always, the scientific basis is unimportant since average viewers like yours truly wouldn't know if it made sense or not.  This particular dimension consists of lots of tall skinny trees and some rather ugly and hungry creatures.  The creature design is pretty imaginative, looking like a dinosaur and giant bug.  It looks more convincing in scenes without the humans.  Attempts at adding humor fail because the writers seem reticent to "broaden" the humor, possibly reluctant to risk their intended "seriousness" quotient.The characters break no new ground in originality, possessing the usual cliches, limiting the actors in their roles.  Joe Flanigan is an appealing hero with the usual "done wrong" history.  John Rhys-Davies shows up in a small role.  The rest of the cast mostly serve as requisite munchies.The movie's conclusion is a real rip-off most likely to generate a sequel, but I am not too pleased with it.FEROCIOUS PLANET is a palpable time-waster but won't go down in history.

reviewText: I picked this up because I'm a fan of Joe Flanigan ("Stargate: Atlantis"), but wasn't expecting much. Most of the movies in the Maneater series are claustrophobic looking (like they were filmed entirely on the same acre of land) or the special effects are really cheap. This was better, however. The monster does look kind of thin, but the movie reminds you more of an old "Twilight Zone" episode than a cheap direct-to-video movie. Flanigan is fun, there's some nice humor, and the conclusion is a little open ended, making you wonder what lie ahead. If they had spent a little more money on the CGI, it would have been quite a nice little movie.
summary: Better than most in the Maneater Series

reviewText: Even though the character development failed to present any real depth and stayed very close, and predictably so, to their stereotypes, this comes off as a solid sci-fi offering.  Of course, it being a Syfy  channel original, it has the normal thin plot that is common with most of these originals.  What elevates this to a higher level is the better than average, and actually good creature development and fx.  This may not be a must have, but it is a nice to have addition to your science fiction collection.There is much predictability with the story line and character development but if you are willing to accept that as a given, it can be moderately enjoyable.  The acting is not bad, it is the development of the story and multiple weak points in the writing that makes it seem worse than it truly is.  It has the normal network TV style violence and themes, and just a small amount of adult language that is mild by todays standards and unheard of 20 years ago.Basically, it is about a disgraced military colonel, a handful of enlisted men, group of board members, and group of scientist gathered together for the unveiling of a new "clean energy" source and, more importantly a device allowing a glimpse into parallel universes, of which there are thousands.  Of course, there is the unexpected malfunction ending in the transportation of this group into one of those universes.  Here they encounter some (very good) creatures with nasty dispositions and must battle these while attempting to make repairs and return home.  There are a couple of twist in the end that are easily foreseen, but still entertaining enough as revealed.This may make this particular film sound worse than it actually is, but that is not my intention and am not implying it should be passed by.  It is head and shoulders above much of the "Maneater"  dubbed Syfy movies and a decent watch.  If it were possible I would have given it a 3 1/2 star rating because it is a little better than "okay"  as Amazon's 3 star rating is defined.  Buy it cheap and you'll be good-to-go.

reviewText: "Ferocious Planet" (2011) is about a group of office people who are accidently teleported to another world via an experimental device that opens windows to parallel dimensions. The forested world looks like earth but it's inhabited by ferocious beasts the size of dinosaurs. The group do everything in their power to survive and find a way back.Before watching this one I fast-forwarded through it and didn't think I'd like it, but -- after viewing -- I have to admit that I enjoyed it for what it is. It's both a story of exploration (of the new planet) and survival. The former gives it a sense of mystery and the latter an air of tension.There are a couple of good women, but they have office apparel on the whole time, which isn't a big deal; I just prefer women in cavegirl outfits in these types of movies, lol (like Beth Rogan in the 1961 version of "Mysterious Island" or Annabelle Wallis and Hannah Tointon in 2010's excellent "The Lost Future").Most people seem to be attracted to this film because Joe Flanigan stars in it; having never watched "Stargate: Atlantis", this was my first exposure to him.The film runs 88 minutes and was shot in Ireland.BOTTOM LINE: "Ferocious Planet" is nothing to get excited over, but it is a solid Grade-B creature feature with a compelling survival situation and the anxiety and thrills thereof.GRADE: B- (or a weak 4 Stars)
summary: Can they make it back alive?
